Langgraph Deployment pointers

To deploy LangGraph agents in Azure Databricks, the recommended approach involves using the Databricks Mosaic AI Agent Framework to build and serve the agent as a REST API endpoint via Databricks Apps.

***Prerequisites***
An Azure Databricks workspace with Databricks Runtime 13.3 ML or above.
The Databricks CLI installed and configured with a Personal Access Token (PAT) or OAuth.
Required Python packages: databricks-langchain, langgraph, and mlflow.
An LLM endpoint (e.g., from Azure OpenAI or Databricks Model Serving) capable of function calling.

1. Deployment Steps

1.1 Author your LangGraph Agent:
1.1.1 Develop your agent logic, defining nodes (agent, tools) and the control flow graph, in a Databricks notebook or local Python files.
1.1.2 Integrate Databricks components like Unity Catalog tools or Vector Search indexes using the databricks-langchain library to provide data access.

1.2 Prepare for Deployment:
1.2.1 Wrap your LangGraph agent code using the MLflow langchain flavor. This makes it compatible with Databricks deployment features and enables automatic tracing with MLflow.
1.2.2 nsure all necessary API keys (e.g., OPENAI_API_KEY, DATABRICKS_TOKEN) are securely managed, preferably using Databricks secrets or the Mosaic AI Gateway.

1.3 Deploy using Databricks Apps:
1.3.1 Use a template (recommended): Start from a pre-built agent template (e.g., agent-openai-agents-sdk) from the Databricks app templates repository to get a production-ready application structure with a conversational UI and a REST API.
1.3.2 Manual deployment: If you build from scratch, you'll need to define an application structure that exposes your agent via a REST API using a server like uvicorn. The databricks apps CLI commands are used to manage the app lifecycle:
databricks apps create <app-name>
databricks sync . "/Workspace/Users/$DATABRICKS_USERNAME/<app-name>" to sync local code
databricks apps deploy <app-name> to deploy the application to a compute resource in your workspace.


1.4 Monitor and Trace:
1.4.1 Enable MLflow autologging (mlflow.langchain.autolog()) to automatically capture the graph's execution traces and log them to your MLflow experiment.
1.4.2 Use the MLflow UI in Databricks to monitor agent performance, debug loops, and evaluate the agent's behavior in production.


