#wrapping the model 1.2.1
```python

from mlflow.models.signature import ModelSignature
from mlflow.types.schema import Schema, ColSpec

# (Optional but recommended) define a signature so serving knows the shape.
# For chat, the PyFunc wrapper accepts a list[dict] or list[BaseMessage]-like.
input_schema  = Schema([ColSpec("string", name="messages")])  # simple form
output_schema = Schema([ColSpec("string", name="output")])
signature = ModelSignature(inputs=input_schema, outputs=output_schema)

with mlflow.start_run() as run:
    logged = mlflow.langchain.log_model(
        lc_model=graph,                # <--- your Runnable (LangGraph compiled)
        artifact_path="langgraph_agent",
        input_example={"messages": [ {"type":"human", "content":"hi"} ]},
        signature=signature,           # optional
        pip_requirements=[
            "langgraph", "langchain-core", "databricks-langchain", "mlflow"
        ],                             # makes env portable/reproducible
        registered_model_name="my_langgraph_agent"  # optional registry
    )

print("Model URI:", logged.model_uri)
``` 

This packages your graph and its environment as an MLflow model with the LangChain flavor, giving you a portable artifact you can load and serve. [mlflow.org]
If you prefer to create the artifact locally first, you can use mlflow.langchain.save_model() and then mlflow.register_model() or mlflow.pyfunc.load_model().
After saving/logging your LangGraph model, you can load and test it locally with:
loaded = mlflow.pyfunc.load_model("path_or_uri")
loaded.predict(...)

```python

